description: From Middle English bitle, bityl, bytylle, from Old English bitula, bitela, bītel (“beetle”), from Proto-West Germanic *bitilō, *bītil, froom Proto-Germanic *bitilô, *bītilaz (“that which tends to bite, biter, beetle”), equivalent to bite +‎ -le. Cognate with Old High German bicco (“beetle”), Danish bille (“beetle”), Icelandic bitil, bitul (“a bite, bit”), Faroese bitil (“small piece, bittock”).

entries.meaning: Any of numerous species of insect in the order Coleoptera characterized by a pair of hard, shell-like front wings which cover and protect a pair of rear wings when at rest.
(uncountable) A game of chance in which players attempt to complete a drawing of a beetle, different dice rolls allowing them to add the various body parts.
examples: Guessing competitions were tackled with much enthusiasm, followed by a beetle drive, and judging by the laughter, this was popular with all.

verbs.description: beetle (third-person singular simple present beetles, present participle beetling, simple past and past participle beetled)

entries.meaning: To move (away) quickly, to scurry away.
examples: He beetled off on his vacation.

description: From Middle English bitel-brouwed (“beetle-browed”). Possibly after beetle, from the fact that some beetles have bushy antennae.

adjectives.description: beetle (comparative more beetle, superlative most beetle)

verbs.description: beetle (third-person singular simple present beetles, present participle beetling, simple past and past participle beetled)

entries.meaning: To loom over; to extend or jut.
examples: The heavy chimney beetled over the thatched roof.

description: From Middle English betel, from Old English bȳtl, bīetel (“hammer”), from Proto-West Germanic *bautil (“hammer, mallet”), equivalent to beat +‎ -le. Cognate with Low German Bötel (“mallet”).

entries.meaning: A type of mallet with a large wooden head, used to drive wedges, beat pavements, etc.
A machine in which fabrics are subjected to a hammering process while passing over rollers, as in cotton mills; a beetling machine.

verbs.description: beetle (third-person singular simple present beetles, present participle beetling, simple past and past participle beetled)

entries.meaning: To beat with a heavy mallet.
To finish by subjecting to a hammering process in a beetle or beetling machine.
